text: @averypickford Another approach is: fine, say ‚Äúequal‚Äù when the world/textbook says ‚Äúcongruent‚Äù. But then there may be times when you‚Äôll need to say ‚Äúextremely equal‚Äù or ‚Äúidentical‚Äù or something, for the (rare, perhaps) case when there are two names for the same triangle.

text:
@averypickford @solidangles Which is to say that names of object can be considered as objects themselves!

3+4=7

but 

‚Äú3+4‚Äù‚â†‚Äù7"
bbox_coords: NA NA NA NA NA NA NA NA
name: Justin Lanier
description:
Math postdoc at UChicago. Organizer of SUBgroups with @MarissaKawehi; paraDIGMS with @matthewando
and @blviray as well.

text:
@averypickford @solidangles Well, doesn‚Äôt it matter whether we‚Äôre talking about objects, or representations of objects? (Or, names/expressions of objects?)

As expressions 3+4 and 7 are different, & we can talk about their different properties as expressions. But they both identically name the same number.
bbox_coords: NA NA NA NA NA NA NA NA
name: Justin Lanier
description:
Math postdoc at UChicago. Organizer of SUBgroups with @MarissaKawehi; paraDIGMS with @matthewando
and @blviray as well.

name: Justin Lanier
description:

text: @averypickford (If I were being more precise, what we usually call a triangle is actually an abtract metric triangle along with an embeddding in the plane; so you can have the underlying triangles being equal, but the embeddings are different, in terms of position.)
bbox_coords: NA NA NA NA NA NA NA NA
name: Justin Lanier
description:
Math postdoc at UChicago. Organizer of SUBgroups with @MarissaKawehi; paraDIGMS with @matthewando
and @blviray as well.

text: @averypickford But you can have two different triangles (one in the first quadrant and one in the third quadrant, say) that are not equal, but they are congruent. This is just not something that happens with numbers in the same way.
bbox_coords: NA NA NA NA NA NA NA NA
name: Justin Lanier
description:
Math postdoc at UChicago. Organizer of SUBgroups with @MarissaKawehi; paraDIGMS with @matthewando
and @blviray as well.

text:
@averypickford So ‚Äúequal‚Äù, as we use it for numbers, is a very strong way of being the same!

Analagously, just as we say 1+4+2=2+4+1, we might say ‚àÜABC=‚àÜCBA. They name the same object.
bbox_coords: NA NA NA NA NA NA NA NA
name: Justin Lanier
description:
Math postdoc at UChicago. Organizer of SUBgroups with @MarissaKawehi; paraDIGMS with @matthewando
and @blviray as well.

text:
@averypickford In math we want a variety of words (& symbols) that mean ‚Äúthe same‚Äù, for different strengths of sameness.

When are two numbers are equal? Well‚Ä¶every number is really only equal to itself. When we say 4+5=9, we‚Äôre really saying that these are two ways of naming the same number.

text: Otherwise everyone is operating in their own disjointed way, where mediocre and harmful practices just  ‚Äúare what they are‚Äù, and a lack of reflection or wider context or wider sense of collective purpose all for plausible deniability.

text:
What can change this?

In my mind, one thing that is necessary is for the stakeholders‚Äîincluding the people in positions to make changes‚Äîto come together to better understand the challenges, the failures, and the successes.

To listen to people who are doing it better.
bbox_coords: NA NA NA NA NA NA NA NA
name: Justin Lanier
description:
Math postdoc at UChicago. Organizer of SUBgroups with @MarissaKawehi; paraDIGMS with @matthewando
and @blviray as well.

text:
The attention of university math departments is often not on their graduate students. There are many other priorities, and this again stands in contrast to the K-12 setting.

Graduate students and their well-being is too often an afterthought.
bbox_coords: NA NA NA NA NA NA NA NA
name: Justin Lanier
description:
Math postdoc at UChicago. Organizer of SUBgroups with @MarissaKawehi; paraDIGMS with @matthewando
and @blviray as well.

text:
Worse, our math graduate programs collectively function in all kinds of exclusionary ways.

This can be verified both from first-hand accounts from students with marginalized identities, as well as from the data about their admissions and graduation outcomes.
bbox_coords: NA NA NA NA NA NA NA NA
name: Justin Lanier
description:
Math postdoc at UChicago. Organizer of SUBgroups with @MarissaKawehi; paraDIGMS with @matthewando
and @blviray as well.

text:
I have heard so many personal accounts of graduate students being pretty miserable in their programs‚Äîand these are folks who have chosen to purse math at the graduate level because they love it so much!

Our programs are not as good as they could be.
bbox_coords: NA NA NA NA NA NA NA NA
name: Justin Lanier
description:
Math postdoc at UChicago. Organizer of SUBgroups with @MarissaKawehi; paraDIGMS with @matthewando
and @blviray as well.

text:
I‚Äôve loved being a part of that work and participating in those communities; I‚Äôve seen all kinds of snippets of this work first hand.

In contrast, the scene in math graduate education is not in so good of shape. There is good work being done, but it is scattered.
bbox_coords: NA NA NA NA NA NA NA NA
name: Justin Lanier
description:
Math postdoc at UChicago. Organizer of SUBgroups with @MarissaKawehi; paraDIGMS with @matthewando
and @blviray as well.

text:
There is so much thought, care, work, organization, discourse, research, & energy put into making K-12 math experiences as good as they can be, for all students.

So many models, so much collaboration, so many resources. It‚Äôs a work in progress, but the work is there, & visible.
